rComments: A very good prof and doable course, I wish I spent more time reviewing for the final for this course. Her exams and tests are fair game and she is very helpful during office hours, and replying to emails. Just go to lectures and pay attemntion to the examples and textbook questions you would do well.

She is a good prof and honestly if you keep up to date with her lectures and do a decent amount of work you should be able to do well. She is the fairest Professor on utsc campus, very helpful when you reach her office hours, approachable, and most responsive to her emails. Honestly, I switched my program in hopes to do more courses with her.
The best teacher

Although she is a very caring and generous prof (and I really admire that), her lectures are quite disorganized, and she spends too much time teaching us stats software, which we only needed for a small assignment. I was not learning much in her lectures.
Excellent presentation of course material.

I honestly can't say that I enjoyed her lectures. Prof. had a tendency to trail off in what she was discussing and was a bit too vague in class. However, the extra material she puts online make the content easy to learn. She has summary videos as well as detailed slides. I used her slides for studying and got an A+ on the midterm. Good overall.

Prof. Aslemand is very approachable and caring. She makes statistical concepts straightforward. She gives tons of examples in lectures that you can refer to. Appreciate the extra bonus marks that she offers to helps students (e.g., UTSCs AEHC).

Shes a good prof and answers questions and is really helpful however half the time you wont understand what shes saying because shes either rushing and shes not good at explaining or shes laughing at her own jokes that nobody gets. I only took this course for a credit and Im glad its almost over.
She is an amazing prof and an amazing person.

I've heard great this about this prof and decided to take her course during the summer. The tutorial and homework questions are easy The midterm however was brutal. She changed the entire structure of the test, so it's all short answers and the allotted time short so a lot of people didn't finish. Last years avg was 78%, mine is 58% on the midterm.

I really love this professor's passion for teaching statistics. She made the class enjoyable. Really accessible outside of class. Her slides are really detailed though, and sometimes I feel that shes going a bit too fast. Overall good prof but her lecturing style wasnt for me sadly.

Really appreciated Prof. Asals teaching statistics. Course structure is well-organized. You need to keep up with weekly contents to do well in the course. Thanks for the lecture videos records. Tests are multiple-choice based but we are given a model test to practice. Tutorial sessions are very helpful. Wish she teaches more statistics courses.

The lecture slides don't explain things well, its basically the same as the textbook but with more pictures. The PSPP and SDA are usually walkthrough as well. Most of it is online, but good luck trying to understand anything. FSGs are useful apparently and the lectures explain better, but its very tempting not to go to class since most is online.
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Prof. Aslemand taught the course material very straightforward. Her lectures were easy to understand for an intro statistics course and she incorporates many real-life studies into her examples. The midterm and exam were both fairly made and marked (both multiple choice); just make sure to keep up with the homework.

Best prof ever. Really responsive to emails, overall really accessible for help. I really love her pace in lectures. The course is neatly organized. I really appreciate that she includes weekly checkups though.
The best
She is one of the best profs i've had at UofT. She is really caring and explains the difficult concepts in an easy way. I would surely take this prof again in my future courses.

Asal is a very approachable prof who is available to help you. I like the pace and the organization of the course (specially if you can't recall intro concepts). She gives lots of demonstrations, which is so helpful for knowing exactly what to do. She simplifies hard concepts really well. Thanks!

Absolutely horrible. She doesn't know how to teach and spends far too much time literally copying things from lecture slides onto the chalk board. What we learn in lectures does not help us answer homework questions (you have to reread the entire textbook to find the answers). It's the 5th week and we're still doing STA220 review.

In my opinion, no math course is easy. I see math as a language, if you don't understand the language it's hard to communicate hence if you don't get math, you don't get the concept. Asal will take her time and if runs out of time you can meet her during office hours or even outside. She will accommodate the heck out of your schedule. BEST PROF!

Asal was amazing! As a non math person I ended up with a 90 because I went to class and did the homework. Everything is super straight forward she really holds your hand through everything. Emailing her is great too and so are her office hours. If you show up she wants you to pass!
Best Prof at UTSC. Love her teaching and actually enjoyed statistics.

I never knew a professor could be passionate about statistics until I met Asal. She was great, and would have her again if I needed another stats course. The group project was not exactly necessary but I enjoyed it.

Asal takes her time with you. She may go slow but that's because she wants everyone at the same pace in the course. She is very understanding when you don't understand the course content and she is willing to meet with you outside office hours to accommodate your schedule. Find another prof who does voice-overs of lectures like she does. Shes great

Prof. Asal is very dedicated and cares a lot for her students' success. She gives lots of opportunities to do well. She does a great job of making statistics relevant for social sciences students. A very approachable professor. Her lectures and the structure of her course is very organized. She uploads voice over of her lecture notes - very useful

Asal is a great instructor. Although her lecture style isn't the greatest (at the end rushed three weeks of material in one because she was so behind in teaching OTL), she is really caring and willing to help. She has excellent teaching attitudes and she really cares for her students' success. Her exams are really fair.

Asal is an awesome prof :)) she is very supportive and gives tons of examples in lectures. She also provides voice over lecture notes which helps for reviewing concepts before exams. If haven't taken a math course for a long time, you have no problem taking it with her. She cares a lot for her students' success.

She is an excellent stats prof :) She explains the materials thoroughly and is always available for help. She definitely wants you to do well. Also, she makes her lectures really fun. There is a group project in the course and it was the best experience we had in our group. We got a chance to select a topic that interest us and work as a group.

Aslemand is a good prof - she cares about her students' success. She posted weekly lecture videos to explain the concepts and her slides were posted online so often times attending the lecture wasn't necessary. The group project was v boring tbh. But the tutorials were easy. Just do textbook problems and practice tutorial quizzes to ace the exam.

Most helpful and down to earth prof at UTSC! If you have to take this course, take it with her. Her lectures are clear and she walks you through tons of examples. As long as you show up to class and take decent notes, you should have no problem getting an A in the course.

I really like the passionate part about her teaching. Yes, she can sometime be confusing, and yes sometime the material might be a little difficult to follow, but Asal does put effort in to make the class the best as she can. If you read over her lecture notes and supplement yourself with textbook notes, it is very hard not to do well in class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: I stopped going to lectures halfway through the course and still got perfect in all the quizzes and did well on the midterm simply by doing tons of practice questions. She is confusing, disorganized, but a nice person who is excited about stats. The course itself is good but this professor acts as if she invented the best teaching methods ever. NOT
